    • Constructor Detail

      • ParentCommand

        public ParentCommand()
        Creates a parent command instance. For this class to successfully execute a command, register(PluginCommand) must be invoked. This constructor will iterate through all methods on the runtime class of this instance to determine which ones represent a subcommand, as determined by the CommandMethod annotation.

    • Method Detail

      • initializeParameterTypes

        protected void initializeParameterTypes(java.util.Set<java.lang.Class<?>> paramTypes,
                            java.util.Map<java.lang.Class<?>,java.lang.Object> defaultParams)
        Called by the superclass during execution of the superclass constructor when, if applicable, the subclass is expected to add its own parameter types (that it supports) to the appropriate sets and maps. Initializing the supported and default parameter collections at any point other than in this method will result in an IllegalStateException during initialization because they were initialized too late.

        If the subclass does not add support for additional parameter types beyond the default, this method does not have to be overriden.

        The default implementation of this method is not where the default supported types are added to the collections. Therefore, if extending ParentCommand directly, it is unneccesary to call the superclass method. The default implementation of this method does nothing.

        It is not necessary to add enum types to the sets directly in this method, as they are parsed automatically by the ParentCommand implementation of parseParameter(String, Class). Enum types do not need to be added to this set, however if parsing behavior for enum types is overriden in the subclass implementation of parseParameter(String, Class), it is expected that the type will be found in the set.

        Any call to getSupportedParameterTypes() or getDefaultParameterValues() within this method would result in infinite recursion, however a safeguard is in place against this. Please use the parameters which represent these variables instead of using those methods.

        Parameters:
        paramTypes - A reference to the set of parameter types that are supported for parsing by this class.
        defaultParams - A reference to the map that maps parameter type values to default instances to use (if the argument is not specified). null is the default if it is not in this map, so reference types need not be added to this set unless the implementation wishes to provide custom default values for reference types.

      • helpCommand

        @CommandMethod(aliases={"help","?"},
               description="Displays help for this command.")
public final void helpCommand(CommandInvocationContext<CommandSender,?> context,
                                               @Optional@Argument(name="page")
                                               int page)
        Represents the default subcommand, which displays command help. This method is always implemented by the ParentCommand class for consistency. It is also required that ParentCommand implements this method because it requires raw access to the list of registered subcommands.

      • getHelpHeader

        protected java.lang.String getHelpHeader()
        Get a String which is used as the header of help pages for this command. This string is passed as a format string, with a formatting argument passed to String.format of one integral value. Simpler implementations can assume that the first instance of "%d" within the string will be replaced with the page number. More complex visual displays may wish to use other formatting options with this format string. The code which uses this method does not provide coloring by default. The default implementation uses a color of aqua as the prefix, but this will not appear without inclusion in the returned string. Subclasses are free to choose any color they wish for the help header.
        Returns:
        The help page header for this command.
        See Also:
        String.format(String, Object...)

      • getDefaultParameterValues

        protected final java.util.Map<java.lang.Class<?>,java.lang.Object> getDefaultParameterValues()

        Returns:

      • parseParameter

        protected java.lang.Object parseParameter(java.lang.String argument,
                              java.lang.Class<?> type)
                                   throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException,
                                          java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException
        Parses an argument, written in human-readable string form, to be of the specified type. Methods which derive from this method should call the superclass method as an attempted parse after attempting to parse the argument themselves, as the superclass call chain will ultimately throw the appropriate exception if no derived class can parse the argument.
        Parameters:
        argument - The argument in string form to parse. If this value is null, the default value in the Java compiler for fields of type type should be returned. This is null for reference types, 0 for most numerical types, and false for booleans.
        type - The Class of the argument that is being parsed. If this value is equivalent to String.class, it is expected that the argument itself is returned.
        Returns:
        argument represented as an instance of type.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - If argument is not deserializable to an instance of type. This exception should not be thrown if argument is null, in which case null (or the appropriate default) should be returned. However, it must be thrown if type is null.
        java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException - If the specified type cannot be deserialized by this method.
